In [[Luxemburgish]] '''Spuerkeess''', in French '''Banque et Caisse d'Épargne de l'État''', is the leading national financial institution founded in 1856 and governed by the law of March 24, 1989. BCEE is a commercial bank wholly owned by the Luxembourgish State.

Nowadays, it provides all the functions of a [[commercial bank]], including [[retail banking]] and [[private banking]]. In terms of total assets BCEE is the third-largest bank in Luxembourg and the largest bank with domestic capital.<ref>[https://thebanks.eu/articles/banks-in-Luxembourg Banks in Luxembourg]</ref>

== History ==
Spuerkees was founded by [[William III of the Netherlands|Grand Duke William III]] as "Caisse d'Épargne de l'État du Grand-Duché de Luxembourg" due to a Law on February 21. 1856. The board of directors had three members and had their first meeting on August 18. 1859 under the presidency of Professor [[:lb:Nicolas Martha|Nicolas Martha]]. Headquarters of the Spuerkees at that time were seated in [[Haus Ketter]] in [[:lb:Dräikinneksgaass|Dräikinneksgaass]] in the city, while their desk offices were at the [[Krautmaart]], at the headquarters of the government commission, which is today's [[Grand Ducal Palace, Luxembourg|Palais]].

Since 1862 it was allowed that foreigners could deposit their money at the Spuerkees. The trust of the Public was high from the first day on, one of the reasons the deposit already reached an amount of one Million [[Franc]] in 1869.

